{"title_page": "Alexandria University", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n|name              = Alexandria University\n|native_name_lang  = ar\n|image             = Alexandria University logo.jpg\n|motto             =\n|established       = 1938\n|type              = [[Public university|Public]]\n|president         = Dr. Essam El-Kurdi\n|vice-president    = \n|students          = 152305\n|undergrad         = 143553\n|postgrad          = 8752\n|city              = [[Alexandria]]\n|country           = [[Egypt]]\n|campus            = [[Urban area|Urban]]\n|former_names      = Azez I University (1938\u20131952) \n|free_label        = Number Of Faculties\n|free              = 23\n|website           = {{url|http://alexu.edu.eg}}\n|logo              =\n|staff             = 7402\n}}\n'''Alexandria University''' ({{lang-ar|\u062c\u0627\u0645\u0639\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0633\u0643\u0646\u062f\u0631\u064a\u0629}}) is a public university in [[Alexandria]], [[Egypt]]. It was established in 1938 as a satellite of [[Cairo University|Fouad University]] (the name of which was later changed to Cairo University), becoming an independent entity in 1942. It was known as Farouk University until the [[Egyptian Revolution of 1952]] when its name was changed to the University of Alexandria. [[Taha Hussein]] was the founding [[Rector (academia)|rector]] of Alexandria University. It is now the second largest university in Egypt and has many affiliations to various universities for ongoing [[research]].\n\nAlexandria University is one of the largest universities in Egypt, and the third university established after Cairo University and the American University in Cairo. Alexandria University has 21 faculties and 3 institutes<ref>https://www.alexu.edu.eg/index.php/en/faculties-centers Alexandria University's faculties</ref> that teach different types of social, medical, engineering, mathematics and other science.The university had other branches in Egypt outside Alexandria in Damanhour<ref>http://damanhour.edu.eg/En/Pages/Page.aspx?id=15 Damanhour Branch</ref> and Matrouh <ref>https://www.youm7.com/story/2017/9/25/%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B5%D9%88%D8%B1-%D9%85%D8%AD%D8%A7%D9%81%D8%B8-%D9%85%D8%B7%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%AD-%D8%A7%D9%81%D8%AA%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%AD-%D8%AC%D8%A7%D9%85%D8%B9%D8%A9-%D9%85%D8%B7%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%AD-%D8%B1%D8%B3%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%A7-%D9%8A%D9%86%D8%A7%D9%8A%D8%B1-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%82%D8%A8%D9%84/3428922 Matrouh separated from Alexandria University and turned into an independent university-Arabic source</ref> which later became two independent universities.Other branches have been set up outside Egypt in Juba, South Sudan,<ref>https://www.jubamonitor.com/egypt-to-open-alexandria-university-branch-in-s-sudan/ Juba Branch</ref> and in N'Djamena,<ref>https://www.alexu.edu.eg/index.php/en/2015-11-24-10-38-07/au-media/au-news/4665-n-djamena-branch-celebrates-the-graduation-of-a-new-batch N'djamena branch</ref> the capital of the Republic of Chad.\n\n== Administration ==\n* Dr. Essam El-Kurdi, President of Alexandria University\n* Dr. Hisham Gaber, Vice President for Education and Student Affairs \n* Dr. Alaa Ramadan, Vice President for Community Service and Environmental Development\n\n== Faculties of project management ==\n[[File:Alexandria University.JPG|thumb|Administration building, Alexandria University]]\n\nAt the time it became an independent institution in 1942, it had the following [[faculty (university)|faculties]]:\n* Faculty of Agriculture\n* Faculty of Medicine (1942)\n* Faculty of Arts (1938)\n* Faculty of Commerce\n* [[Faculty of Engineering, Alexandria University|Faculty of Engineering]] (1941)\n* Faculty of Law (1938)\n* [[Faculty of Science, Alexandria University|Faculty of Science]] (1942)\n\nIn 1989, four faculties, located in Alexandria and administered by [[Helwan University]], were annexed to Alexandria University. These are the faculties of [[Agriculture]], [[Fine Arts]], [[Physical Education]] for Boys and Physical Education for Girls.\n\nAlexandria University Holds now 24 Faculties and Institutes as follows:\n* Faculty of Arts (1938)\n* Faculty of Law (1938)\n* Faculty of Commerce (1942)\n* Faculty of Engineering (1942)\n* Faculty of Science (1942)\n* Faculty of Agriculture (1942)\n* Faculty of Medicine (1942)\n* Faculty of Pharmacy (1947)\n* [http://nurs.alexu.edu.eg Faculty of Nursing] (1954)\n* Faculty of Physical Education for Girls (1954)\n* Faculty of Physical Education for Boys (1955)\n* High Institute of Public Health (1956)\n* Faculty of Fine Arts (1957)\n* Faculty of Agriculture (Saba Basha) (1959)\n* Faculty of Education (1966)\n* Faculty of Dentistry (1970)\n* Institute of Graduate Studies and Research (1972)\n* Faculty of Veterinary Medicine (1975)\n* Institute of Medical Research (1975)\n* Faculty of Tourism and Hotels (1982)\n* Faculty of Specific Education (1988)\n* Faculty of Education for Early Childhood (1989) <ref>http://kindg.alexu.edu.eg/index.php/en/ The Faculty of Kindergarten changed its name to the Faculty of Education for Early Childhood </ref>\n* Faculty of Economic Studies & Political Science (2014)\n* Faculty of Computing and Data Science (2019)<ref>https://akhbarelyom.com/news/newdetails/2890665/1/%D8%A5%D9%86%D8%B4%D8%A7%D8%A1-%D9%83%D9%84%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D9%84%D9%84%D8%AD%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D9%88%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%88%D9%85-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A8%D9%8A%D8%A7%D9%86%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A8%D8%AC%D8%A7%D9%85%D8%B9%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A5%D8%B3%D9%83%D9%86%D8%AF%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A9 Establishment of the Faculty of Computing and Data Science-Arabic source\n</ref>\nAlexandria University Also opened branches in African and Middle-Eastern Countries:\n* Chad Branch\n* Iraq Branch\n* South Sudan Branch\n\n== Notable alumni and faculty ==\n* [[William Linn Westermann]] (Visiting Professor 1948) \u2013 American papyrologist\n* [[Yahya El Mashad]] (Faculty of Engineering, 1952) \u2013 Egyptian nuclear physicist\n* [[Mohamed Hashish]] (Faculty of Engineering) \u2013 research scientist best known as the father of the abrasive water jet cutter\n* [[Mohammed Aboul-Fotouh Hassab]] (1913\u20132000) \u2013 professor of gastro-intestinal surgery; creator of surgical procedure known as [[Hassab's decongestion operation]]\n\n* [[Mo Ibrahim]] (Faculty of Engineering) \u2013 Sudanese-British mobile communications entrepreneur and billionaire\n* [[Tawfiq Saleh]] (English literature, 1949) \u2013 film director<ref name=ahram>{{cite news|first=|last=|title=Egyptian renowned film director Tawfiq Saleh dies at 87|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/5/32/79335/Arts--Culture/Film/Egyptian-renowned-film-director-Tawfiq-Saleh-dies-.aspx|work=[[Al-Ahram]]|date=2013-08-18|accessdate=2013-09-14}}</ref>\n* [[Boshra Salem]] \u2013 professor, founder and the Chair of the Department of Environmental Sciences<ref name=\"ICSU\">{{cite news|title=Dr. Boshra Salem inducted into U.S. Department of State\u2019s Women in Science Hall of Fame|url=http://www.icsu.org/news-centre/news/dr.-boshra-salem-inducted-into-u.s.-department-of-state2019s-women-in-science-hall-of-fame|accessdate=10 July 2016|work=International Council for Science|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819171633/http://www.icsu.org/news-centre/news/dr.-boshra-salem-inducted-into-u.s.-department-of-state2019s-women-in-science-hall-of-fame|archive-date=19 August 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Ahmed Zewail]] (Faculty of Science, 1967) \u2013 Nobel Prize in Chemistry, 1999<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/chemistry/laureates/1999/|title=The Nobel Prize in Chemistry 1999|publisher=Nobelprize.org|accessdate=2013-02-04}}</ref>\n* [[Azer Bestavros]] (Faculty of Engineering, 1984) \u2013 Warren Distinguished Professor of Computer Science, Boston University, Boston, US\n* [[Rebecca Joshua Okwaci]] (English language, literature, and translation) \u2013 South Sudanese politician, and the Minister of Telecommunications and Postal Services in the Government of the Republic of South Sudan\n*[[Khadry AbdelGalil]] (faculty of dentistry.1964)-discoverer of surgical glue used for stopping brain aneurysm bleeding.\n\n== Ranking ==\nAlexandria University was ranked 147th worldwide based on Times Higher Education's World University Rankings 2010\u20132011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/world-university-rankings/2010-2011/top-200.html|title=World University Rankings 2010\u20132011|publisher=Timeshighereducation.co.uk|accessdate=2013-02-04}}</ref> The 2010 rankings were controversial, as a single [[Mohamed El Naschie|professor]]'s  practice of publishing a great number of articles in a journal of which he himself was the editor was identified as a crucial contributing factor for the high rating of Alexandria University.<ref name=\"NYTimes1\">[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/15/education/15iht-educLede15.html Questionable Science Behind Academic Rankings], ''The New York Times'' 14 November 2010.</ref>\nAlexandria University is ranked 301+ worldwide based on Times Higher Education's World University Rankings 2011\u20132012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/world-university-rankings/2011-2012/301-350.html|title=World University Rankings 2011\u20132012|publisher=Timeshighereducation.co.uk|accessdate=2013-02-04}}</ref> Alexandria University is ranked 601+ worldwide based on QS World University Rankings 2011/12.<ref>http://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2011?page=11</ref> It was ranked 701+ in the QS World University Rankings 2014/2015.\n\n{{As of|2017}}, it is 916th worldwide and 2nd in Egypt according to Webometrics' ranking of world universities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.webometrics.info/en/aw/Egypt|title=Ranking Web of Universities: Egypt|accessdate=24 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Alexandria#Education|Educational institutions in Alexandria]]\n* [[Education in Egypt]]\n* [[List of universities in Egypt]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.alexu.edu.eg|Alexandria University official website}}\n\n{{Port-City University League}}\n{{UNIMED}}\n\n{{coord|31|12|07|N|29|54|19|E|type:edu_region:EG|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:1938 establishments in Egypt]]\n[[Category:Alexandria University|*]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1938]]\n[[Category:Forestry education]]\n[[Category:Universities in Egypt]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university\n|name              = Alexandria University\n|native_name_lang  = ar\n|image             = Alexandria University logo.jpg\n|motto             =\n|established       = 1938\n|type              = [[Public university|Public]]\n|president         = Dr. Essam El-Kurdi\n|vice-president    = \n|students          = 152305\n|undergrad         = 143553\n|postgrad          = 8752\n|city              = [[Alexandria]]\n|country           = [[Egypt]]\n|campus            = [[Urban area|Urban]]\n|former_names      = Azez I University (1938\u20131952) \n|free_label        = Number Of Faculties\n|free              = 23\n|website           = {{url|http://alexu.edu.eg}}\n|logo              =\n|staff             = 7402\n}}\n'''Alexandria University''' ({{lang-ar|\u062c\u0627\u0645\u0639\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0633\u0643\u0646\u062f\u0631\u064a\u0629}}) is a public university in [[Alexandria]], [[Egypt]]. It was established in 1938 as a satellite of [[Cairo University|Fouad University]] (the name of which was later changed to Cairo University), becoming an independent entity in 1942. It was known as Farouk University until the [[Egyptian Revolution of 1952]] when its name was changed to the University of Alexandria. [[Taha Hussein]] was the founding [[Rector (academia)|rector]] of Alexandria University. It is now the second largest university in Egypt and has many affiliations to various universities for ongoing [[research]].\n\nAlexandria University is one of the largest universities in Egypt, and the third university established after Cairo University and the American University in Cairo. Alexandria University has 21 faculties and 3 institutes<ref>https://www.alexu.edu.eg/index.php/en/faculties-centers Alexandria University's faculties</ref> that teach different types of social, medical, engineering, mathematics and other science.The university had other branches in Egypt outside Alexandria in Damanhour<ref>http://damanhour.edu.eg/En/Pages/Page.aspx?id=15 Damanhour Branch</ref> and Matrouh <ref>https://www.youm7.com/story/2017/9/25/%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B5%D9%88%D8%B1-%D9%85%D8%AD%D8%A7%D9%81%D8%B8-%D9%85%D8%B7%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%AD-%D8%A7%D9%81%D8%AA%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%AD-%D8%AC%D8%A7%D9%85%D8%B9%D8%A9-%D9%85%D8%B7%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%AD-%D8%B1%D8%B3%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%A7-%D9%8A%D9%86%D8%A7%D9%8A%D8%B1-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%82%D8%A8%D9%84/3428922 Matrouh separated from Alexandria University and turned into an independent university-Arabic source</ref> which later became two independent universities.Other branches have been set up outside Egypt in Juba, South Sudan,<ref>https://www.jubamonitor.com/egypt-to-open-alexandria-university-branch-in-s-sudan/ Juba Branch</ref> and in N'Djamena,<ref>https://www.alexu.edu.eg/index.php/en/2015-11-24-10-38-07/au-media/au-news/4665-n-djamena-branch-celebrates-the-graduation-of-a-new-batch N'djamena branch</ref> the capital of the Republic of Chad.\n\n== Administration ==\n* Dr. Essam El-Kurdi, President of Alexandria University\n* Dr. Hisham Gaber, Vice President for Education and Student Affairs \n* Dr. Alaa Ramadan, Vice President for Community Service and Environmental Development\n\n== Faculties of project management ==\n[[File:Alexandria University.JPG|thumb|Administration building, Alexandria University]]\n\nAt the time it became an independent institution in 1942, it had the following [[faculty (university)|faculties]]:\n* Faculty of Agriculture\n* Faculty of Medicine (1942)\n* Faculty of Arts (1938)\n* Faculty of Commerce\n* [[Faculty of Engineering, Alexandria University|Faculty of Engineering]] (1941)\n* Faculty of Law (1938)\n* [[Faculty of Science, Alexandria University|Faculty of Science]] (1942)\n\nIn 1989, four faculties, located in Alexandria and administered by [[Helwan University]], were annexed to Alexandria University. These are the faculties of [[Agriculture]], [[Fine Arts]], [[Physical Education]] for Boys and Physical Education for Girls.\n\nAlexandria University Holds now 24 Faculties and Institutes as follows:\n* Faculty of Arts (1938)\n* Faculty of Law (1938)\n* Faculty of Commerce (1942)\n* Faculty of Engineering (1942)\n* Faculty of Science (1942)\n* Faculty of Agriculture (1942)\n* Faculty of Medicine (1942)\n* Faculty of Pharmacy (1947)\n* [http://nurs.alexu.edu.eg Faculty of Nursing] (1954)\n* Faculty of Physical Education for Girls (1954)\n* Faculty of Physical Education for Boys (1955)\n* High Institute of Public Health (1956)\n* Faculty of Fine Arts (1957)\n* Faculty of Agriculture (Saba Basha) (1959)\n* Faculty of Education (1966)\n* Faculty of Dentistry (1970)\n* Institute of Graduate Studies and Research (1972)\n* Faculty of Veterinary Medicine (1975)\n* Institute of Medical Research (1975)\n* Faculty of Tourism and Hotels (1982)\n* Faculty of Specific Education (1988)\n* Faculty of Education for Early Childhood (1989) <ref>http://kindg.alexu.edu.eg/index.php/en/ The Faculty of Kindergarten changed its name to the Faculty of Education for Early Childhood </ref>\n* Faculty of Economic Studies & Political Science (2014)\n* Faculty of Computing and Data Science (2019)<ref>https://akhbarelyom.com/news/newdetails/2890665/1/%D8%A5%D9%86%D8%B4%D8%A7%D8%A1-%D9%83%D9%84%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D9%84%D9%84%D8%AD%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D9%88%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%88%D9%85-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A8%D9%8A%D8%A7%D9%86%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A8%D8%AC%D8%A7%D9%85%D8%B9%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A5%D8%B3%D9%83%D9%86%D8%AF%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A9 Establishment of the Faculty of Computing and Data Science-Arabic source\n</ref>\nAlexandria University Also opened branches in African and Middle-Eastern Countries:\n* Chad Branch\n* Iraq Branch\n* South Sudan Branch\n\n== Notable alumni and faculty ==\n* [[William Linn Westermann]] (Visiting Professor 1948) \u2013 American papyrologist\n* [[Yahya El Mashad]] (Faculty of Engineering, 1952) \u2013 Egyptian nuclear physicist\n* [[Mohamed Hashish]] (Faculty of Engineering) \u2013 research scientist best known as the father of the abrasive water jet cutter\n* [[Mohammed Aboul-Fotouh Hassab]] (1913\u20132000) \u2013 professor of gastro-intestinal surgery; creator of surgical procedure known as [[Hassab's decongestion operation]]\n\n* [[Mo Ibrahim]] (Faculty of Engineering) \u2013 Sudanese-British mobile communications entrepreneur and billionaire\n* [[Tawfiq Saleh]] (English literature, 1949) \u2013 film director<ref name=ahram>{{cite news|first=|last=|title=Egyptian renowned film director Tawfiq Saleh dies at 87|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/5/32/79335/Arts--Culture/Film/Egyptian-renowned-film-director-Tawfiq-Saleh-dies-.aspx|work=[[Al-Ahram]]|date=2013-08-18|accessdate=2013-09-14}}</ref>\n* [[Boshra Salem]] \u2013 professor, founder and the Chair of the Department of Environmental Sciences<ref name=\"ICSU\">{{cite news|title=Dr. Boshra Salem inducted into U.S. Department of State\u2019s Women in Science Hall of Fame|url=http://www.icsu.org/news-centre/news/dr.-boshra-salem-inducted-into-u.s.-department-of-state2019s-women-in-science-hall-of-fame|accessdate=10 July 2016|work=International Council for Science|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819171633/http://www.icsu.org/news-centre/news/dr.-boshra-salem-inducted-into-u.s.-department-of-state2019s-women-in-science-hall-of-fame|archive-date=19 August 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Ahmed Zewail]] (Faculty of Science, 1967) \u2013 Nobel Prize in Chemistry, 1999<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/chemistry/laureates/1999/|title=The Nobel Prize in Chemistry 1999|publisher=Nobelprize.org|accessdate=2013-02-04}}</ref>\n* [[Azer Bestavros]] (Faculty of Engineering, 1984) \u2013 Warren Distinguished Professor of Computer Science, Boston University, Boston, US\n* [[Rebecca Joshua Okwaci]] (English language, literature, and translation) \u2013 South Sudanese politician, and the Minister of Telecommunications and Postal Services in the Government of the Republic of South Sudan\n\n== Ranking ==\nAlexandria University was ranked 147th worldwide based on Times Higher Education's World University Rankings 2010\u20132011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/world-university-rankings/2010-2011/top-200.html|title=World University Rankings 2010\u20132011|publisher=Timeshighereducation.co.uk|accessdate=2013-02-04}}</ref> The 2010 rankings were controversial, as a single [[Mohamed El Naschie|professor]]'s  practice of publishing a great number of articles in a journal of which he himself was the editor was identified as a crucial contributing factor for the high rating of Alexandria University.<ref name=\"NYTimes1\">[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/15/education/15iht-educLede15.html Questionable Science Behind Academic Rankings], ''The New York Times'' 14 November 2010.</ref>\nAlexandria University is ranked 301+ worldwide based on Times Higher Education's World University Rankings 2011\u20132012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/world-university-rankings/2011-2012/301-350.html|title=World University Rankings 2011\u20132012|publisher=Timeshighereducation.co.uk|accessdate=2013-02-04}}</ref> Alexandria University is ranked 601+ worldwide based on QS World University Rankings 2011/12.<ref>http://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2011?page=11</ref> It was ranked 701+ in the QS World University Rankings 2014/2015.\n\n{{As of|2017}}, it is 916th worldwide and 2nd in Egypt according to Webometrics' ranking of world universities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.webometrics.info/en/aw/Egypt|title=Ranking Web of Universities: Egypt|accessdate=24 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Alexandria#Education|Educational institutions in Alexandria]]\n* [[Education in Egypt]]\n* [[List of universities in Egypt]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.alexu.edu.eg|Alexandria University official website}}\n\n{{Port-City University League}}\n{{UNIMED}}\n\n{{coord|31|12|07|N|29|54|19|E|type:edu_region:EG|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:1938 establishments in Egypt]]\n[[Category:Alexandria University|*]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1938]]\n[[Category:Forestry education]]\n[[Category:Universities in Egypt]]\n", "name_user": "Koko brazil", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eNotable alumni and faculty:<ref></ref>)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexandria_University"}
{"title_page": "Erinna", "text_new": "{{About|the Greek poet}}\n[[File:Sappho and Erinna in a Garden at Mytilene.jpg|thumb|300px|''Sappho and Erinna in a Garden at Mytilene'' by [[Simeon Solomon]]]]\n'''Erinna''' ({{IPAc-en|\u1d7b|\u02c8|r|\u026a|n|\u0259}}; {{lang-grc-gre|\u1f2c\u03c1\u03b9\u03bd\u03bd\u03b1}}) was an [[Ancient Greece|ancient Greek]] poet.  She is best known for her long poem, ''The Distaff'', a three-hundred line [[dactylic hexameter|hexameter]] lament for her childhood friend Baucis, who had died shortly after marriage.  A large fragment of this poem was discovered in 1928 at [[Oxyrhynchus]] in Egypt.  Along with ''The Distaff'', three epigrams ascribed to Erinna are known, preserved in the ''[[Greek Anthology]]''.  Biographical details about Erinna's life are uncertain. She is generally thought to have lived in the first half of the fourth century BC, though some ancient traditions have her as a contemporary of [[Sappho]]; [[Tilos|Telos]] is generally considered to be her most likely birthplace, but [[Tinos|Tenos]], [[Teos]], [[Rhodes]], and [[Lesbos]] are all also mentioned by ancient sources as her home.  \n\n==Life==\nLittle ancient evidence about Erinna's life survives, and the testimony which does is often contradictory.  Her dates are uncertain.  According to the [[Suda]], she was one of Sappho's companions, placing her floruit in the sixth century BC.{{sfn|Levin|1962|p=193}}  The latest date given for Erinna in the ancient testimonia is that provided by [[Eusebius]], who suggests the mid-fourth century BC.{{sfn|Levin|1962|p=194}}  Scholars now tend to believe that Erinna was an early Hellenistic poet.{{sfn|Levin|1962|p=193}}\n\nAncient testimony is divided on where Erinna was from: possibilities include [[Teos]], [[Tilos|Telos]], [[Tinos|Tenos]], [[Mytilene]], and [[Rhodes]].{{sfn|Arthur|1980|p=57}}  Sylvia Barnard argues that Erinna was from Telos on the grounds of her dialect,{{sfn|Barnard|1978|p=204}} though Donald Levin notes that while based on [[Doric Greek|Doric]], Erinna's dialect is a literary creation and does not accurately reflect her own native dialect.{{sfn|Levin|1962|p=195}}  It is likely that Erinna was born into a wealthy family, and would have been taught to read and write poetry \u2013 Teos, one of Erinna's possible birthplaces, is one of the few places in the ancient Greek world where epigraphical evidence that girls were educated survives.{{sfn|Pomeroy|1978|pp=19\u201320}}\n\nThree epigrams preserved in the [[Greek Anthology]] suggest that Erinna died young \u2013 according to Asclepiades shortly after composing the ''Distaff'' aged 19, though the earliest source to explicitly fix her date of death at age 19 is the Suda.{{sfn|West|1977|pp=95\u20136}}  Marylin B. Arthur, however, argues that though the character of Erinna in the ''Distaff'' was 19, it is not necessarily the case that she did compose the poem when she was that age.{{sfn|Arthur|1980|p=56}}\n\n==Works==\n===''The Distaff''===\n[[File:Ossirinco, frammento di papiro con alakata (conocchia) di erinna, 190 dc ca. (psi IX 1090).jpg|right|thumb|PSI 1090, which preserves fragments of 54 lines of ''Distaff'']]\nErinna's fame is founded on her 300-line [[hexameter]] poem, the ''Distaff''.  The poem, supposedly composed when she was just nineteen,{{sfn|West|1977|p=95}} is a lament for her friend Baucis, who died shortly after her marriage.{{sfn|Rayor|2005|p=59}}  Unlike most ancient Greek hexameter poetry, which was written in an Ionian dialect, ''Distaff'' was written in a mixture of Aeolian and Doric.{{sfn|Plant|2004|p=48}}\n\n''Distaff'' survives only in fragments.  Parts of 54 lines, of which only one line is complete, are known,{{sfn|Rayor|2005|loc=n.10}} preserved on a second century AD papyrus from [[Oxyrhynchus]], PSI 1090.{{sfn|West|1977|p=97}}  Three other fragments of hexameter poetry attributed to Erinna survive, two quoted by [[Stobaeus]] and one by [[Athenaeus]].  One of the quotations in Stobaeus matches up with line 46 of PSI 1090;{{sfn|Rauk|1989|loc=n.5}} both of the other fragments also probably come from ''Distaff''.{{sfn|Plant|2004|p=49}}  Another papyrus fragment, [[Papyrus Oxyrhynchus 8]], was identified by [[Maurice Bowra]] as possibly being from ''Distaff'';{{sfn|Plant|2004|p=49}} however [[Martin Litchfield West]] dismisses this on dialectical grounds.{{sfn|West|1977|pp=113&ndash;114}}\n\nIn the first half of the long surviving fragment of the ''Distaff'', the narrator recalls her childhood with Baucis.  She speaks of a game the two played, described by [[Julius Pollux]], who calls it ''chelichelone'' (\"torty-tortoise\"), and of their fear of [[Mormo]], a Greek [[bogeyman|bogeywoman]].{{sfn|Snyder|1991|pp=94&ndash;95}}  Following this, there is a short section on Baucis' forgetfulness &ndash; the text is fragmentary, but possibly the narrator is saying that when she married, Baucis forgot the childhood which has just been described.  Finally, there is a reference to the narrator's inability to view a corpse, and two mentions of the word ''aidos'' (\"shame\") &ndash; presumably Baucis has died, and the narrator is ashamed that she cannot mourn her friend.  At this point the text becomes too fragmentary to reconstruct it further.{{sfn|Snyder|1991|p=95}}\n\nThe ''Distaff'' is a literary version of the ''goos'' &ndash; the lament chanted by the female relatives of the deceased during the ''[[Ancient Greek funeral and burial practices|prothesis]]'' (laying out the body).{{sfn|Manwell|2005|p=76}}{{sfn|Skinner|1982|p=266}}  Earlier literary depictions of the ''goos'', also in hexameter verse, are found in the ''[[Iliad]]'', and several scholars have seen Erinna's poem as making use of this literary precedent.  Marylin Skinner identifies three examples of the ''goos'' in the ''Iliad'': [[Briseis]]' lament for [[Patroclus]], [[Andromache]]'s on seeing [[Achilles]] dragging [[Hector]]'s corpse around the walls of Troy, and the lament sung by Andromache, [[Hecuba]], and [[Helen of Troy|Helen]] at Hector's wake.{{sfn|Skinner|1982|p=266}}  Skinner identifies \"marked thematic and verbal correspondences\" between the ''Distaff'' and the songs of mourning in the ''Iliad''.  For instance, Erinna's recollections of her early life with Baucis parallel Andromache's of her son's interactions with Hector, and Helen's of Hector supporting her when she first came to Troy.{{sfn|Skinner|1982|p=267}}  Diane Rayor specifically identifies Briseis' lament as a model for the ''Distaff''.{{sfn|Rayor|2005|p=59}}\n\nAlong with Homer, the other major literary influence on Erinna's ''Distaff'' was [[Sappho]].{{sfn|Stehle|2001|p=193}}  Kathryn Gutzwiller has argued that this incorporation of Sapphic themes into a poem of lamentation is Erinna's way of feminising a work based on a Homeric model.{{sfn|Manwell|2005|p=76}}  John Rauk notes particular similarities with [[Sappho 94|fragment 94]],{{sfn|Rauk|1989|p=101}} with both works on themes of remembrance and forgetting.{{sfn|Rauk|1989|pp=111&ndash;112}} Diane Rayor, however, rejects this, disputing Rauk's belief that Sappho 94 is a farewell to a companion who is leaving to marry.{{sfn|Rayor|2005|p=59}}\n\n===Epigrams===\nAlong with the fragments of the ''Distaff'', three epigrams attributed to Erinna survive.{{sfn|Manwell|2005|p=72}}  These are in the Doric dialect,{{sfn|Levin|1962|p=195}} and all three are preserved in the Greek Anthology.{{sfn|Rauk|1989|p=103}}  Two of these are, like ''Distaff'', about the death of Baucis;{{sfn|West|1977|p=101}} the third, which is similar to poems by [[Nossis]], is about a portrait of a girl called Agatharchis.{{sfn|West|1977|p=115}}  The two Baucis-epigrams are in the style of ancient epitaphs, though the fact there are two suggests that neither was in fact written as a tomb inscription.{{sfn|Snyder|1989|p=91}}  \n\nThe authorship of these is disputed:{{sfn|Arthur|1980|p=53}} Rauk and West both argue that none of the epigrams were authored by Erinna.{{sfn|Rauk|1989|p=103}}{{sfn|West|1977|p=114}}  Rauk suggests that the two Baucis-epigrams were written by later authors as a tribute to Erinna,{{sfn|Rauk|1989|p=104}} and West notes that there is nothing in the epigrams which the authors could not have learnt from ''Distaff''.{{sfn|West|1977|p=115}}  The third epigram is described by Rauk as a \"commonplace\", containing \"nothing to support Erinna's authorship\",{{sfn|Rauk|1989|p=103}} and West suggests that Nossis is a more likely author.{{sfn|West|1977|p=116}}  On the other hand, Sarah Pomeroy argues for Erinna's authorship of all three epigrams,{{sfn|Pomeroy|1978|p=21}} and Jane McIntosh Snyder describes them as \"probably by Erinna\".{{sfn|Snyder|1991|p=86}}{{efn|Other scholars, including {{harvnb|Barnard|1978}}, {{harvnb|Manwell|2005}}, and {{harvnb|Rayor|2005}} accept the epigrams as being authored by Erinna without explicitly addressing the dispute.}}\n\n==Reception==\nIn antiquity, Erinna was highly regarded; the only Greek woman poet to be better thought of was Sappho,{{sfn|West|1977|p=95}} though today she is little-known.[[Antipater of Thessalonica]] included her in his list of \"nine earthly muses\".{{sfn|Arthur|1980|p=53}}  Several other epigrams collected in the Greek Anthology praise her, and in [[Meleager of Gadara|Meleager]]'s \"Garland\" her work is compared to the \"sweet, maidenly coloured crocus\".{{sfn|Plant|2004|p=48}}  The only negative ancient testimony about Erinna comes from an epigram by Antiphanes (''[[Palatine Anthology|AP]]'' 11.322),{{sfn|Levin|1962|pp=193&ndash;194}} which itself attests to Erinna's high reputation among the followers of [[Callimachus]].{{sfn|Rauk|1989|p=103}}  All of this ancient testimony about Erinna suggests that she was a major figure in Hellenistic poetry.{{sfn|Snyder|1991|p=90}}\n\nToday, so little of Erinna's work survives that it is difficult to judge her poetry,{{sfn|Snyder|1991|p=86}} though what has survived of ''Distaff'' does, according to Ian Plant, bear out the poem's ancient reputation.{{sfn|Plant|2004|p=48}}  In addition, Eva Stehle sees Erinna's poetry as significant as one of the very few sources of evidence about the relationship between mothers and daughters in the ancient Greek world.{{sfn|Stehle|2001|p=179}}  Erinna has also been read by feminist scholars as part of a female poetic tradition in ancient Greece, along with others including Sappho and Nossis.{{sfn|Greene|2005|p=139}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Works cited==\n* {{cite journal|last=Arthur|first=Marylin B.|title=The Tortoise and the Mirror: Erinna PSI 1090|journal=The Classical World|volume=74|issue=2|year=1980|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Barnard|first=Sylvia|title=Hellenistic Women Poets|journal=The Classical Journal|volume=73|issue=3|year=1978|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Levin|first=Donald Norman|title=Quaestiones Erinneanae|journal=Harvard Studies in Classical Philology|volume=66|year=1962|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Manwell|first=Elizabeth|chapter=''Dico Ergo Sum'': Erinna's Voice and Poetic Reality|editor-last=Greene|editor-first=Ellen|title=Women Poets in Ancient Greece and Rome|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press|year=2005|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Plant|first=I. M.|title=Women Writers of Ancient Greece and Rome: an Anthology|year=2004|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press|location=Norman|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Pomeroy|first=Sarah|title=Supplementary Notes on Erinna|journal=Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Papyrologie und Epigraphik|volume=32|year=1978|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Rauk|first=John|title=Erinna's Distaff and Sappho's Fr. 94|journal=Greek, Roman, and Byzantine Studies|year=1989|volume=30|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Rayor|first=Diane|chapter=The Power of Memory in Erinna and Sappho|editor-last=Greene|editor-first=Ellen|title=Women Poets in Ancient Greece and Rome|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press|year=2005|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Skinner|first=Marilyn B.|journal=The Classical World|year=1982|volume=75|issue=5|title=Briseis, the Trojan Women, and Erinna|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Snyder|first=Jane McIntosh|title=The Woman and the Lyre: Women Writers in Classical Greece and Rome|publisher=SIU Press|location=Carbondale|year=1991|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Stehle|first=Eva|editor1-last=Lardinois|editor1-first=Andr\u00e9|editor2-last=McClure|editor2-first=Laura|title=Making Silence Speak: Women's Voices in Greek Literature and Society|chapter=The Good Daughter: Mothers' Tutelage in Erinna's ''Distaff'' and Fourth-Century Epitaphs|publisher=Princeton University Press|location=Princeton|year=2001|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last=West|first=Martin Litchfield|year=1977|title=Erinna|journal=Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Papyrologie und Epigraphik|volume=25|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikisourcelang|el|\u0389\u03c1\u03b9\u03bd\u03bd\u03b1|\u1f2c\u03c1\u03b9\u03bd\u03bd\u03b1}}\n{{Commons category}}\n{{EB1911 poster|Erinna}}\n*[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0104&query=head%3D%236657 A dictionary of Greek and Roman biography and mythology (ed. William Smith): Erinna] (compare the same dictionary's [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0104;query=id%3D%236656;layout=;loc= entry on an alleged second poet with the same name])\n*[http://www.attalus.org/poetry/erinna.html English translation of a papyrus fragment of Erinna's poem]\n*[http://www.bartleby.com/246/888.html Poem about Erinna]\n*{{ws|[[s:The Golden Violet with its Tales of Romance and Chivalry and Other Poems/Erinna|Erinna, by L. E. L.]]}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:4th-century BC women writers]]\n[[Category:4th-century BC writers]]\n[[Category:4th-century BC poets]]\n[[Category:Ancient Rhodian poets]]\n[[Category:People from the South Aegean]]\n[[Category:Ancient Greek women poets]]\n[[Category:1st-millennium BC births]]\n[[Category:1st-millennium BC deaths]]\n[[Category:Doric Greek poets]]\n[[Category:Aeolic Greek poets]]\n[[Category:Epigrammatists of the Greek Anthology]]\n[[Category:Women satirists]]\n[[Category:4th-century BC Greek women]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the Greek poet}}\n[[File:Sappho and Erinna in a Garden at Mytilene.jpg|thumb|300px|''Sappho and Erinna in a Garden at Mytilene'' by [[Simeon Solomon]]]]\n'''Erinna''' ({{IPAc-en|\u1d7b|\u02c8|r|\u026a|n|\u0259}}; {{lang-grc-gre|\u1f2c\u03c1\u03b9\u03bd\u03bd\u03b1}}) was an [[Ancient Greece|ancient Greek]] poet.  She is best known for her long poem, ''The Distaff'', a three-hundred line [[dactylic hexameter|hexameter]] lament for her childhood friend Baucis, who had died shortly after marriage.  A large fragment of this poem was discovered in 1928 at [[Oxyrhynchus]] in Egypt.  Along with ''The Distaff'', three epigrams ascribed to Erinna are known, preserved in the ''[[Greek Anthology]]''.  Biographical details about Erinna's life are uncertain. She is generally thought to have lived in the first half of the fourth century BC, though some ancient traditions have her as a contemporary of [[Sappho]]; [[Tilos|Telos]] is generally considered to be her most likely birthplace, but [[Tinos|Tenos]], [[Teos]], [[Rhodes]], and [[Lesbos]] are all also mentioned by ancient sources as her home.  \n\n==Life==\nLittle ancient evidence about Erinna's life survives, and the testimony which does is often contradictory.  Her dates are uncertain.  According to the [[Suda]], she was one of Sappho's companions, placing her floruit in the sixth century BC.{{sfn|Levin|1962|p=193}}  The latest date given for Erinna in the ancient testimonia is that provided by [[Eusebius]], who suggests the mid-fourth century BC.{{sfn|Levin|1962|p=194}}  Scholars now tend to believe that Erinna was an early Hellenistic poet.{{sfn|Levin|1962|p=193}}\n\nAncient testimony is divided on where Erinna was from: possibilities include [[Teos]], [[Tilos|Telos]], [[Tinos|Tenos]], [[Mytilene]], and [[Rhodes]].{{sfn|Arthur|1980|p=57}}  Sylvia Barnard argues that Erinna was from Telos on the grounds of her dialect,{{sfn|Barnard|1978|p=204}} though Donald Levin notes that while based on [[Doric Greek|Doric]], Erinna's dialect is a literary creation and does not accurately reflect her own native dialect.{{sfn|Levin|1962|p=195}}  It is likely that Erinna was born into a wealthy family, and would have been taught to read and write poetry \u2013 Teos, one of Erinna's possible birthplaces, is one of the few places in the ancient Greek world where epigraphical evidence that girls were educated survives.{{sfn|Pomeroy|1978|pp=19\u201320}}\n\nThree epigrams preserved in the [[Greek Anthology]] suggest that Erinna died young \u2013 according to Asclepiades shortly after composing the ''Distaff'' aged 19, though the earliest source to explicitly fix her date of death at age 19 is the Suda.{{sfn|West|1977|pp=95\u20136}}  Marylin B. Arthur, however, argues that though the character of Erinna in the ''Distaff'' was 19, it is not necessarily the case that she did compose the poem when she was that age.{{sfn|Arthur|1980|p=56}}\n\n==Works==\n===''The Distaff''===\n[[File:Ossirinco, frammento di papiro con alakata (conocchia) di erinna, 190 dc ca. (psi IX 1090).jpg|right|thumb|PSI 1090, which preserves fragments of 54 lines of ''Distaff'']]\nErinna's fame is founded on her 300-line [[hexameter]] poem, the ''Distaff''.  The poem, supposedly composed when she was just nineteen,{{sfn|West|1977|p=95}} is a lament for her friend Baucis, who died shortly after her marriage.{{sfn|Rayor|2005|p=59}}  Unlike most ancient Greek hexameter poetry, which was written in an Ionian dialect, ''Distaff'' was written in a mixture of Aeolian and Doric.{{sfn|Plant|2004|p=48}}\n\n''Distaff'' survives only in fragments.  Parts of 54 lines, of which only one line is complete, are known,{{sfn|Rayor|2005|loc=n.10}} preserved on a second century AD papyrus from [[Oxyrhynchus]], PSI 1090.{{sfn|West|1977|p=97}}  Three other fragments of hexameter poetry attributed to Erinna survive, two quoted by [[Stobaeus]] and one by [[Athenaeus]].  One of the quotations in Stobaeus matches up with line 46 of PSI 1090;{{sfn|Rauk|1989|loc=n.5}} both of the other fragments also probably come from ''Distaff''.{{sfn|Plant|2004|p=49}}  Another papyrus fragment, [[Papyrus Oxyrhynchus 8]], was identified by [[Maurice Bowra]] as possibly being from ''Distaff'';{{sfn|Plant|2004|p=49}} however [[Martin Litchfield West]] dismisses this on dialectical grounds.{{sfn|West|1977|pp=113&ndash;114}}\n\nIn the first half of the long surviving fragment of the ''Distaff'', the narrator recalls her childhood with Baucis.  She speaks of a game the two played, described by [[Julius Pollux]], who calls it ''chelichelone'' (\"torty-tortoise\"), and of their fear of [[Mormo]], a Greek [[bogeyman|bogeywoman]].{{sfn|Snyder|1991|pp=94&ndash;95}}  Following this, there is a short section on Baucis' forgetfulness &ndash; the text is fragmentary, but possibly the narrator is saying that when she married, Baucis forgot the childhood which has just been described.  Finally, there is a reference to the narrator's inability to view a corpse, and two mentions of the word ''aidos'' (\"shame\") &ndash; presumably Baucis has died, and the narrator is ashamed that she cannot mourn her friend.  At this point the text becomes too fragmentary to reconstruct it further.{{sfn|Snyder|1991|p=95}}\n\nThe ''Distaff'' is a literary version of the ''goos'' &ndash; the lament chanted by the female relatives of the deceased during the ''[[Ancient Greek funeral and burial practices|prothesis]]'' (laying out the body).{{sfn|Manwell|2005|p=76}}{{sfn|Skinner|1982|p=266}}  Earlier literary depictions of the ''goos'', also in hexameter verse, are found in the ''[[Iliad]]'', and several scholars have seen Erinna's poem as making use of this literary precedent.  Marylin Skinner identifies three examples of the ''goos'' in the ''Iliad'': [[Briseis]]' lament for [[Patroclus]], [[Andromache]]'s on seeing [[Achilles]] dragging [[Hector]]'s corpse around the walls of Troy, and the lament sung by Andromache, [[Hecuba]], and [[Helen of Troy|Helen]] at Hector's wake.{{sfn|Skinner|1982|p=266}}  Skinner identifies \"marked thematic and verbal correspondences\" between the ''Distaff'' and the songs of mourning in the ''Iliad''.  For instance, Erinna's recollections of her early life with Baucis parallel Andromache's of her son's interactions with Hector, and Helen's of Hector supporting her when she first came to Troy.{{sfn|Skinner|1982|p=267}}  Diane Rayor specifically identifies Briseis' lament as a model for the ''Distaff''.{{sfn|Rayor|2005|p=59}}\n\nAlong with Homer, the other major literary influence on Erinna's ''Distaff'' was [[Sappho]].{{sfn|Stehle|2001|p=193}}  Kathryn Gutzwiller has argued that this incorporation of Sapphic themes into a poem of lamentation is Erinna's way of feminising a work based on a Homeric model.{{sfn|Manwell|2005|p=76}}  John Rauk notes particular similarities with [[Sappho 94|fragment 94]],{{sfn|Rauk|1989|p=101}} with both works on themes of remembrance and forgetting.{{sfn|Rauk|1989|pp=111&ndash;112}} Diane Rayor, however, rejects this, disputing Rauk's belief that Sappho 94 is a farewell to a companion who is leaving to marry.{{sfn|Rayor|2005|p=59}}\n\n===Epigrams===\nAlong with the fragments of the ''Distaff'', three epigrams attributed to Erinna survive.{{sfn|Manwell|2005|p=72}}  These are in the Doric dialect,{{sfn|Levin|1962|p=195}} and all three are preserved in the Greek Anthology.{{sfn|Rauk|1989|p=103}}  Two of these are, like ''Distaff'', about the death of Baucis;{{sfn|West|1977|p=101}} the third, which is similar to poems by [[Nossis]], is about a portrait of a girl called Agatharchis.{{sfn|West|1977|p=115}}  The two Baucis-epigrams are in the style of ancient epitaphs, though the fact there are two suggests that neither was in fact written as a tomb inscription.{{sfn|Snyder|1989|p=91}}  \n\nThe authorship of these is disputed:{{sfn|Arthur|1980|p=53}} Rauk and West both argue that none of the epigrams were authored by Erinna.{{sfn|Rauk|1989|p=103}}{{sfn|West|1977|p=114}}  Rauk suggests that the two Baucis-epigrams were written by later authors as a tribute to Erinna,{{sfn|Rauk|1989|p=104}} and West notes that there is nothing in the epigrams which the authors could not have learnt from ''Distaff''.{{sfn|West|1977|p=115}}  The third epigram is described by Rauk as a \"commonplace\", containing \"nothing to support Erinna's authorship\",{{sfn|Rauk|1989|p=103}} and West suggests that Nossis is a more likely author.{{sfn|West|1977|p=116}}  On the other hand, Sarah Pomeroy argues for Erinna's authorship of all three epigrams,{{sfn|Pomeroy|1978|p=21}} and Jane McIntosh Snyder describes them as \"probably by Erinna\".{{sfn|Snyder|1991|p=86}}{{efn|Other scholars, including {{harvnb|Barnard|1978}}, {{harvnb|Manwell|2005}}, and {{harvnb|Rayor|2005}} accept the epigrams as being authored by Erinna without explicitly addressing the dispute.}}\n\n==Reception==\nIn antiquity, Erinna was highly regarded; the only Greek woman poet to be better thought of was Sappho,{{sfn|West|1977|p=95}} though today she is little-known.{{sfn|Arthur|1980|p=53}}  [[Antipater of Thessalonica]] included her in his list of \"nine earthly muses\".{{sfn|Arthur|1980|p=53}}  Several other epigrams collected in the Greek Anthology praise her, and in [[Meleager of Gadara|Meleager]]'s \"Garland\" her work is compared to the \"sweet, maidenly coloured crocus\".{{sfn|Plant|2004|p=48}}  The only negative ancient testimony about Erinna comes from an epigram by Antiphanes (''[[Palatine Anthology|AP]]'' 11.322),{{sfn|Levin|1962|pp=193&ndash;194}} which itself attests to Erinna's high reputation among the followers of [[Callimachus]].{{sfn|Rauk|1989|p=103}}  All of this ancient testimony about Erinna suggests that she was a major figure in Hellenistic poetry.{{sfn|Snyder|1991|p=90}}\n\nToday, so little of Erinna's work survives that it is difficult to judge her poetry,{{sfn|Snyder|1991|p=86}} though what has survived of ''Distaff'' does, according to Ian Plant, bear out the poem's ancient reputation.{{sfn|Plant|2004|p=48}}  In addition, Eva Stehle sees Erinna's poetry as significant as one of the very few sources of evidence about the relationship between mothers and daughters in the ancient Greek world.{{sfn|Stehle|2001|p=179}}  Erinna has also been read by feminist scholars as part of a female poetic tradition in ancient Greece, along with others including Sappho and Nossis.{{sfn|Greene|2005|p=139}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Works cited==\n* {{cite journal|last=Arthur|first=Marylin B.|title=The Tortoise and the Mirror: Erinna PSI 1090|journal=The Classical World|volume=74|issue=2|year=1980|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Barnard|first=Sylvia|title=Hellenistic Women Poets|journal=The Classical Journal|volume=73|issue=3|year=1978|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Levin|first=Donald Norman|title=Quaestiones Erinneanae|journal=Harvard Studies in Classical Philology|volume=66|year=1962|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Manwell|first=Elizabeth|chapter=''Dico Ergo Sum'': Erinna's Voice and Poetic Reality|editor-last=Greene|editor-first=Ellen|title=Women Poets in Ancient Greece and Rome|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press|year=2005|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Plant|first=I. M.|title=Women Writers of Ancient Greece and Rome: an Anthology|year=2004|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press|location=Norman|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Pomeroy|first=Sarah|title=Supplementary Notes on Erinna|journal=Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Papyrologie und Epigraphik|volume=32|year=1978|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Rauk|first=John|title=Erinna's Distaff and Sappho's Fr. 94|journal=Greek, Roman, and Byzantine Studies|year=1989|volume=30|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Rayor|first=Diane|chapter=The Power of Memory in Erinna and Sappho|editor-last=Greene|editor-first=Ellen|title=Women Poets in Ancient Greece and Rome|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press|year=2005|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Skinner|first=Marilyn B.|journal=The Classical World|year=1982|volume=75|issue=5|title=Briseis, the Trojan Women, and Erinna|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Snyder|first=Jane McIntosh|title=The Woman and the Lyre: Women Writers in Classical Greece and Rome|publisher=SIU Press|location=Carbondale|year=1991|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Stehle|first=Eva|editor1-last=Lardinois|editor1-first=Andr\u00e9|editor2-last=McClure|editor2-first=Laura|title=Making Silence Speak: Women's Voices in Greek Literature and Society|chapter=The Good Daughter: Mothers' Tutelage in Erinna's ''Distaff'' and Fourth-Century Epitaphs|publisher=Princeton University Press|location=Princeton|year=2001|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last=West|first=Martin Litchfield|year=1977|title=Erinna|journal=Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Papyrologie und Epigraphik|volume=25|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikisourcelang|el|\u0389\u03c1\u03b9\u03bd\u03bd\u03b1|\u1f2c\u03c1\u03b9\u03bd\u03bd\u03b1}}\n{{Commons category}}\n{{EB1911 poster|Erinna}}\n*[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0104&query=head%3D%236657 A dictionary of Greek and Roman biography and mythology (ed. William Smith): Erinna] (compare the same dictionary's [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0104;query=id%3D%236656;layout=;loc= entry on an alleged second poet with the same name])\n*[http://www.attalus.org/poetry/erinna.html English translation of a papyrus fragment of Erinna's poem]\n*[http://www.bartleby.com/246/888.html Poem about Erinna]\n*{{ws|[[s:The Golden Violet with its Tales of Romance and Chivalry and Other Poems/Erinna|Erinna, by L. E. L.]]}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:4th-century BC women writers]]\n[[Category:4th-century BC writers]]\n[[Category:4th-century BC poets]]\n[[Category:Ancient Rhodian poets]]\n[[Category:People from the South Aegean]]\n[[Category:Ancient Greek women poets]]\n[[Category:1st-millennium BC births]]\n[[Category:1st-millennium BC deaths]]\n[[Category:Doric Greek poets]]\n[[Category:Aeolic Greek poets]]\n[[Category:Epigrammatists of the Greek Anthology]]\n[[Category:Women satirists]]\n[[Category:4th-century BC Greek women]]\n", "name_user": "Iazyges", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing duplicate citations", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Erinna"}
{"title_page": "Paul Splittorff", "text_new": "{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Paul Splittorff\n|image=Paul Splittorff - Kansas City Royals - 1980.jpg\n|caption=Splittorff in 1980\n|position=[[Pitcher]]\n|bats=Left\n|throws=Left\n|birth_date={{Birth date|1946|10|8}}\n|birth_place=[[Evansville, Indiana]]\n|death_date ={{Death date and age|2011|5|25|1946|10|8}}\n|death_place=[[Blue Springs, Missouri]]\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=September 23\n|debutyear=1970\n|debutteam=Kansas City Royals\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=June 26\n|finalyear=1984\n|finalteam=Kansas City Royals\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=[[Win\u2013loss record (pitching)|Win\u2013loss record]]\n|stat1value=166\u2013143\n|stat2label=[[Earned run average]]\n|stat2value=3.81\n|stat3label=[[Strikeout]]s\n|stat3value=1,057\n|teams=\n*[[Kansas City Royals]] ({{mlby|1970}}\u2013{{mlby|1984}})\n|highlights=\n* [[Kansas City Royals Hall of Fame]]\n}}\n'''Paul William Splittorff Jr.''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|p|l|\u026a|t|\u0254r|f}}; October 8, 1946 \u2013 May 25, 2011)<ref name=NYT>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/26/sports/baseball/paul-splittorff-royals-biggest-winner-dies-at-64.html?_r=1&ref=deathsobituaries|title=Paul Splittorff, Royals\u2019 Biggest Winner, Dies at 64|author=Bruce Weber|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 25, 2011}}</ref> was a [[Major League Baseball]] [[starting pitcher]] who spent his entire career with the [[Kansas City Royals]]. Listed at {{height|ft=6|in=3}}, Splittorff batted and threw [[left-handed]].\n\n==Early years==\nSplittorff was born in [[Evansville, Indiana]] and grew up mostly in [[Arlington Heights, Illinois]].<ref name=NYT/> Arlington High School produced several major league baseball players, including [[Fritz Peterson]], [[Dick Bokelmann]], and [[George Vukovich]].<ref>{{cite news|title=214@100: Splittorff, other notables hail from Old Arlington|url=http://www.dailyherald.com/article/20150616/news/150619205/|accessdate=17 June 2015|publisher=Daily Herald}}</ref>\n\nPeterson and Splittorff pitched against each other twice during their careers, with Peterson winning both matchups.  On August 17, 1971, the Yankees beat the [[Kansas City Royals]] 2-0 at Yankee Stadium (in the days before the [[Designated Hitter]], both pitchers went 0-2 at the plate),<ref>{{cite web|title=August 17, 1971|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA197108171.shtml|website=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=17 June 2015}}</ref> and on August 22, 1975 at the old [[Royals Stadium]], the Indians beat the Royals, 9-5.<ref>{{cite web|title=Friday, August 22, 1975, 7:30PM, Royals Stadium|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/KCA/KCA197508220.shtml|website=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=17 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe was drafted by the Royals in the 25th round of the [[1968 Major League Baseball Draft]] out of [[Morningside College]] in [[Sioux City, Iowa]], where he was a member of [[Delta Sigma Phi]] fraternity and also played basketball.<ref name=NYT/> He pitched for the Corning Royals in 1968 (a year before the major league club existed), and has the distinction of throwing the first pitch in Royals organization history.  He went 28\u201327 with a 4.01 [[earned run average]] in three seasons in the Royals' farm system before receiving his first call to the majors in September {{by|1970}}. He took the loss in his major league debut, pitching seven innings and giving up three [[earned runs]] against the [[Chicago White Sox]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CHA/CHA197009230.shtml|title=Chicago White Sox 6, Kansas City Royals 0|date=September 23, 1970|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com}}</ref>\n\n==Kansas City Royals==\nSplittorff began the {{by|1971}} season with the [[Omaha Royals]], but after going 5\u20132 with a 1.48 ERA in eight starts for Omaha, he earned a second promotion to the majors. He stayed with Kansas City for the rest of the season, going 8\u20139 with a 2.68 ERA.\n\nFrom there, he became a fixture in the Kansas City rotation. He enjoyed his only 20-win season in {{by|1973}}, when he went 20\u201311 with a 3.98 ERA. Splittorff was the starting pitcher in the inaugural game at [[Kauffman Stadium]] (known at the time as Royals Stadium) on April 10, 1973; Splittorff earned the victory that evening in a 12\u20131 rout of the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]].  After finishing second to the [[Oakland Athletics]] three of his first five seasons in the majors, Splittorff and the Royals emerged as [[American League West]] champions in {{by|1976}}.\n\nKansas City faced the [[New York Yankees]] in every [[American League Championship Series]] from 1976 to {{by|1978}}, with the Yankees emerging victorious in all three. For his part, Splittorff was 2\u20130 with a 2.84 ERA against the Yankees in the five appearances he made against them in the ALCS. After both teams missed the playoffs in {{by|1979}}, the Royals and Yankees resumed their postseason rivalry in the [[1980 American League Championship Series]]. Kansas City swept the series, with Splittorff starting the third and deciding game, and receiving a no-decision.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA198010100.shtml|title=1980 American League Championship Series, Game Three|date=October 10, 1980|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com}}</ref> The Royals lost the [[World Series]] in six games to the [[Philadelphia Phillies]] with Splittorff making his only appearance in game six.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/PHI/PHI198010210.shtml|title=1980 World Series, Game Six|date=October 21, 1980|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com}}</ref>\n\nNever an All-Star and usually overshadowed by teammates [[Steve Busby]], [[Dennis Leonard]] and [[Larry Gura]], Splittorff's consistency and longevity resulted in his winning more games than any of them. Splittorff accumulated 166 career victories over a 15-year career with the Royals.\n\nSplittorff retired when his effectiveness faded. At the same time, the Royals had numerous young pitchers coming through the ranks. His final game was on June 26, {{Baseball year|1984}}.\n\n==Personal life==\nAfter his retirement, Splittorff became a television [[color commentator]] for the Royals. He was inducted into the Royals Hall of Fame in {{By|1987}}.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.kansascity.com/2013/07/26/4370092/nobody-comes-close-in-royals-hall.html | title=Nobody comes close in Royals\u2019 Hall of Fame election | publisher=The Kansas City Star | date=July 26, 2013 | accessdate=February 1, 2014 | author=Dutton, Bob}}</ref> He also worked as an analyst for [[Big Eight Conference|Big Eight]] and [[Big 12 Conference|Big 12]] [[college basketball]] telecasts.\n\nOn May 16, 2011, Splittorff's battle with oral cancer and melanoma became public.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.kansascity.com/2011/05/16/2879651_former-royals-pitcher-splittorff.html?storylink=omni_popular |title=Former Royals pitcher Splittorff battling cancer - KansasCity.com |first=Bob |last=Dutton |work=kansascity.com |date=May 16, 2011 |accessdate=May 17, 2011}}</ref> Nine days later, on the morning of May 25, he died in his [[Blue Springs, Missouri]], home at the age of 64.<ref>[http://www.kansascity.com/2011/05/25/2902340/royals-great-paul-splittorff-dies.html Kerkhoff, Blair. \"Royals great Paul Splittorff dies,\" ''The Kansas City'' (MO) ''Star'', Thursday, May 26, 2011.]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Major League Baseball players who spent their entire career with one franchise]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*1976 Baseball Register published by [[The Sporting News]]\n\n==External links==\n{{baseballstats|mlb=122602|br=s/splitpa01|brm=splitt001pau|retro=S/Psplip001}}\n\n{{Kansas City Royals Opening Day starting pitchers}}\n{{Kansas City Royals}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Splittorff, Paul}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:American Methodists]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Indiana]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in Missouri]]\n[[Category:College basketball announcers in the United States]]\n[[Category:Corning Royals players]]\n[[Category:Deaths from oral cancer]]\n[[Category:Deaths from melanoma]]\n[[Category:Kansas City Royals broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Kansas City Royals players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball pitchers]]\n[[Category:Morningside Mustangs baseball players]]\n[[Category:Morningside Mustangs men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Omaha Royals players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Evansville, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in baseball]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games gold medalists for the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Blue Springs, Missouri]]\n[[Category:Baseball players at the 1967 Pan American Games]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Paul Splittorff\n|image=Paul Splittorff - Kansas City Royals - 1980.jpg\n|caption=Splittorff in 1980\n|position=[[Pitcher]]\n|bats=Left\n|throws=Left\n|birth_date={{Birth date|1946|10|8}}\n|birth_place=[[Evansville, Indiana]]\n|death_date ={{Death date and age|2011|5|25|1946|10|8}}\n|death_place=[[Blue Springs, Missouri]]\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=September 23\n|debutyear=1970\n|debutteam=Kansas City Royals\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=June 26\n|finalyear=1984\n|finalteam=Kansas City Royals\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=[[Win\u2013loss record (pitching)|Win\u2013loss record]]\n|stat1value=166\u2013143\n|stat2label=[[Earned run average]]\n|stat2value=3.81\n|stat3label=[[Strikeout]]s\n|stat3value=1,057\n|teams=\n*[[Kansas City Royals]] ({{mlby|1970}}\u2013{{mlby|1984}})\n|highlights=\n* [[Kansas City Royals Hall of Fame]]\n}}\n'''Paul William Splittorff, Jr.''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|p|l|\u026a|t|\u0254r|f}}; October 8, 1946 \u2013 May 25, 2011)<ref name=NYT>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/26/sports/baseball/paul-splittorff-royals-biggest-winner-dies-at-64.html?_r=1&ref=deathsobituaries|title=Paul Splittorff, Royals\u2019 Biggest Winner, Dies at 64|author=Bruce Weber|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 25, 2011}}</ref> was a [[Major League Baseball]] [[starting pitcher]] who spent his entire career with the [[Kansas City Royals]]. Listed at {{height|ft=6|in=3}}, Splittorff batted and threw [[left-handed]].\n\n==Early years==\nSplittorff was born in [[Evansville, Indiana]] and grew up mostly in [[Arlington Heights, Illinois]].<ref name=NYT/> Arlington High School produced several major league baseball players, including [[Fritz Peterson]], [[Dick Bokelmann]], and [[George Vukovich]].<ref>{{cite news|title=214@100: Splittorff, other notables hail from Old Arlington|url=http://www.dailyherald.com/article/20150616/news/150619205/|accessdate=17 June 2015|publisher=Daily Herald}}</ref>\n\nPeterson and Splittorff pitched against each other twice during their careers, with Peterson winning both matchups.  On August 17, 1971, the Yankees beat the [[Kansas City Royals]] 2-0 at Yankee Stadium (in the days before the [[Designated Hitter]], both pitchers went 0-2 at the plate),<ref>{{cite web|title=August 17, 1971|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA197108171.shtml|website=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=17 June 2015}}</ref> and on August 22, 1975 at the old [[Royals Stadium]], the Indians beat the Royals, 9-5.<ref>{{cite web|title=Friday, August 22, 1975, 7:30PM, Royals Stadium|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/KCA/KCA197508220.shtml|website=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=17 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe was drafted by the Royals in the 25th round of the [[1968 Major League Baseball Draft]] out of [[Morningside College]] in [[Sioux City, Iowa]], where he was a member of [[Delta Sigma Phi]] fraternity and also played basketball.<ref name=NYT/> He pitched for the Corning Royals in 1968 (a year before the major league club existed), and has the distinction of throwing the first pitch in Royals