ack ==\n{{track listing\n| all_writing = \n| extra_column = Singer(s)\n| title1 = Sukha Dukha\n| length1 = 4:05\n| extra1 = Aadha Sur, Sarada Adhikari\n| total_length = 4:05\n}}\n\n== Critical Reception ==\n''Dhanapati'' earned \u20b910&nbsp;million in the box office on its first day.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.977mag.net/dhanapati-box-office-collection-dhanapati-crosses-10-million-in-nepalese-box-office-collection/|title=Dhanapati Crosses 10 Million In Nepalese Box Office Collection|date=2017-07-09|work=Nepali Film News|access-date=2017-07-12|language=en-US}}</ref> ''Dhanapati'' received mixed reviews from the Nepalese audience.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2017-07-09/dhanapati-released-to-mixed-reviews.html|title=Dhanapati released to mixed reviews|access-date=2017-07-12|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|tt6580708}}\n\n[[Category:Nepalese films]]\n[[Category:Nepali-language films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Kathmandu]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Dipendra K Khanal]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Khagendra Lamichhane]]\n\n\n{{2010s-Nepali-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Titodutta", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCritical reception:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dhanapati"}
{"title_page": "Philip Davies (British Army officer)", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n|name=Philip Davies\n|birth_date=27 October 1932\n|death_date=\n|birth_place=\n|death_place= \n|image=\n|caption= \n|nickname= \n|allegiance= [[United Kingdom]]\n|serviceyears=\n|rank= [[Major-general (United Kingdom)|Major-General]]\n|branch= [[British Army]]\n|current position= \n|commands=1st Battalion Royal Scots<br>[[19th Light Brigade (United Kingdom)|19th Infantry Brigade]]<br>Land Forces, [[Cyprus]]<br>[[North West District (British Army)|North West District]]\n|unit=\n|battles=[[Korean War]]<br>[[Suez Crisis]]<br>[[Northern Ireland]]\n|awards= [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]]\n|laterwork= \n}}\n[[Major-general (United Kingdom)|Major-General]] '''Philip Middleton Davies''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE}} (born 27 October 1932) is a former [[British Army]] officer.\n\n==Military career==\nEducated at [[Charterhouse School]] and the [[Royal Military Academy Sandhurst]], Davies was commissioned into the [[Royal Scots]] in 1953 and saw action during the [[Korean War]] before being deployed to the [[Suez Canal|Suez Canal Zone]].<ref name=WW>''[[Who's Who (UK)|Who's Who]] 2010'', [[A & C Black]], 2010, {{ISBN|978-1-4081-1414-8}}</ref> He became commanding officer of the 1st Battalion Royal Scots in 1973<ref>Bandit Country| https://www.youtube.com/watch?time_continue=527&v=wcS2LBx3nZ4&feature=emb_logo</ref> and was deployed to [[Northern Ireland]] during [[the Troubles]].<ref name=WW/> He became commander of [[19th Light Brigade (United Kingdom)|19th Infantry Brigade]] in 1977, commander of Land Forces, [[Cyprus]] in 1981 and General Officer Commanding [[North West District (British Army)|North West District]] in 1983 before retiring in 1986.<ref name=commands>{{cite web|url=http://www.gulabin.com/armynavy/pdf/Army%20Commands%201860-.pdf|title=Army Commands|accessdate=2 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Michael Hicks (British Army officer)|Michael Hicks]]}} \n{{s-ttl|title=General Officer Commanding [[North West District (British Army)|North West District]]|years=1983&ndash;1986}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Colin Shortis]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davies, Philip}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Charterhouse School]]\n[[Category:Graduates of the Royal Military Academy Sandhurst]]\n[[Category:British Army generals]]\n[[Category:Royal Scots officers]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n|name=Philip Davies\n|birth_date=27 October 1932\n|death_date=\n|birth_place=\n|death_place= \n|image=\n|caption= \n|nickname= \n|allegiance= [[United Kingdom]]\n|serviceyears=\n|rank= [[Major-general (United Kingdom)|Major-General]]\n|branch= [[British Army]]\n|current position= \n|commands=1st Battalion Royal Scots<br>[[19th Light Brigade (United Kingdom)|19th Infantry Brigade]]<br>Land Forces, [[Cyprus]]<br>[[North West District (British Army)|North West District]]\n|unit=\n|battles=[[Korean War]]<br>[[Suez Crisis]]<br>[[Northern Ireland]]\n|awards= [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]]\n|laterwork= \n}}\n[[Major-general (United Kingdom)|Major-General]] '''Philip Middleton Davies''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE}} (born 27 October 1932) is a former [[British Army]] officer.\n\n==Military career==\nEducated at [[Charterhouse School]] and the [[Royal Military Academy Sandhurst]], Davies was commissioned into the [[Royal Scots]] in 1953 and saw action during the [[Korean War]] before being deployed to the [[Suez Canal|Suez Canal Zone]].<ref name=WW>''[[Who's Who (UK)|Who's Who]] 2010'', [[A & C Black]], 2010, {{ISBN|978-1-4081-1414-8}}</ref> He became commanding officer of the 1st Battalion Royal Scots in 1973 and was deployed to [[Northern Ireland]] during [[the Troubles]].<ref name=WW/> He became commander of [[19th Light Brigade (United Kingdom)|19th Infantry Brigade]] in 1977, commander of Land Forces, [[Cyprus]] in 1981 and General Officer Commanding [[North West District (British Army)|North West District]] in 1983 before retiring in 1986.<ref name=commands>{{cite web|url=http://www.gulabin.com/armynavy/pdf/Army%20Commands%201860-.pdf|title=Army Commands|accessdate=2 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Michael Hicks (British Army officer)|Michael Hicks]]}} \n{{s-ttl|title=General Officer Commanding [[North West District (British Army)|North West District]]|years=1983&ndash;1986}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Colin Shortis]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davies, Philip}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Charterhouse School]]\n[[Category:Graduates of the Royal Military Academy Sandhurst]]\n[[Category:British Army generals]]\n[[Category:Royal Scots officers]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n", "name_user": "Maple leaf eh", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMilitary career:Youtube link with visuals of the individual", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philip_Davies_(British_Army_officer)"}
{"title_page": "Albert Raby", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{refimprove|date=August 2018}}\n{{essay-like|date=April 2009}}\n}}\n\n'''Albert Anderson Raby''' (1933 \u2013 November 23, 1988) was a teacher at [[Chicago]]'s [[Hess Upper Grade Center]]. She gained the support of [[Martin Luther King Jr.]] to desegregate schools and housing in Chicago between 1965 and 1967. Raby was apart of the civil rights movement and helped create the [http://www.encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/221.html Coordinating Council of Community Organizations] (CCCO), the mission of the CCCO was to end segregation in Chicago schools. Raby tried to stay out of the media and public eye so there is little information known about him<ref>{{Citation|title=Ambivalent Discourse: : Rights-based Theories on Minorities|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.5040/9781501301872.ch-003|work=Who Speaks for Roma? : Political Representation of a Transnational Minority Community|publisher=Continuum|isbn=978-0-8264-2880-6|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\n==Early life==\nRaby was born into poverty in Chicago, dropping out of school in the sixth grade. He became involved in a [[trade union|union]], and, after a stint in the army, earned his grammar school diploma at age 24.  He went on to earn his high school diploma immediately after that. He attended day and evening school to earn his high school diploma. In 1960, he earned a teaching degree from [[Chicago Teachers College]] and entered the profession.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://students.com/Albert%20Raby|title=Students.com|website=students.com|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n==Later career==\nRaby was the Director of the Peace Corps in Ghana from 1979\u201382. Afterwards, he returned to Chicago and was the campaign manager for [[Harold Washington]]'s successful mayoral campaign in 1983. Washington appointed him to head the City of Chicago's Commission on Human Relations in May of 1983.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://alchetron.com/Albert-Raby|website=alchetron.com|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n==Death and recognition==\nRaby collapsed and died from a heart attack on November 23, 1988.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kinginstitute.stanford.edu/encyclopedia/raby-albert|title=Raby, Albert|last=University|first=\u00a9 Stanford|last2=Stanford|date=2017-07-05|website=The Martin Luther King, Jr., Research and Education Institute|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10|last3=California 94305}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004 a Chicago Public High School named after Al Raby was opened. Located in the Garfield Park neighborhood, Al Raby High School for Community and Environment focuses on social justice issues as well as geographical information systems.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/columnists/2020/3/12/21176568/mural-raby-high-school-wpa-works-progress-adminitration-edward-millman|title=We can\u2019t learn from art we can\u2019t see|last=Steinberg|first=Neil|date=2020-03-12|website=Chicago Sun-Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{Civil rights movement}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Raby, Albery}}\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:1988 deaths]]\n[[Category:Activists for African-American civil rights]]\n[[Category:People from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Activists from Illinois]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{refimprove|date=August 2018}}\n{{essay-like|date=April 2009}}\n}}\n\n'''Albert Anderson Raby''' (1933 \u2013 November 23, 1988) was a teacher at [[Chicago]]'s [[Hess Upper Grade Center]] who secured the support of [[Martin Luther King Jr.]] to desegregate schools and housing in Chicago between 1965 and 1967. Raby was apart of the civil rights movement and helped create the [http://www.encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/221.html Coordinating Council of Community Organizations] (CCCO), the mission of the CCCO was to end segregation in Chicago schools. Raby tried to stay out of the media and public eye so there is little information known on him<ref>{{Citation|title=Ambivalent Discourse: : Rights-based Theories on Minorities|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.5040/9781501301872.ch-003|work=Who Speaks for Roma? : Political Representation of a Transnational Minority Community|publisher=Continuum|isbn=978-0-8264-2880-6|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\n==Early life==\nRaby was born into poverty in Chicago, dropping out of school in the sixth grade. He became involved in a [[trade union|union]], and, after a stint in the army, earned his grammar school diploma at age 24.  He went on to earn his high school diploma immediately after that. He attended day and evening school to earn his high school diploma. In 1960, he earned a teaching degree from [[Chicago Teachers College]] and entered the profession.\n\n==CCCO formation==\nRaby was a member of the [[Teachers for Integrated Schools]] and helped form the [http://www.encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/221.html Coordinating Council of Community Organizations] (CCCO)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kinginstitute.stanford.edu/encyclopedia/raby-albert|title=Raby, Albert|last=University|first=\u00a9 Stanford|last2=Stanford|date=2017-07-05|website=The Martin Luther King, Jr., Research and Education Institute|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10|last3=California 94305}}</ref> in 1962. In 1963, Raby assisted in organizing the [[Chicago Public School Boycott]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.chicagoreader.com/Bleader/archives/2013/05/20/remembering-chicagos-great-school-boycott-of-1963|title=Remembering Chicago's great school boycott of 1963|last=Joravsky|first=Ben|work=Chicago Reader|access-date=2017-07-19|language=en}}</ref> TFIS selected him to be their delegate to the CCCO. On January 11, 1964, he was appointed the organization's convenor (Anderson and Pickering 129).\n\nWhen the CCCO movement was officially launched, Raby became its co-chairman.<!-- Image with unknown copyright status removed: [[Image:RabyKing.jpg|thumb|right|Al Raby with Martin Luther King, Jr.]] -->\n\nAs a member of the Agenda Committee, Raby assisted in choosing open housing as the initial campaign for the movement. Along with King in July 1966, he attended the initial meeting with Mayor [[Richard J. Daley]] where the demands of the movement were presented.  Raby served as a leader of open housing marches, using his position as a local leader to draw upon those in Chicago communities affected by housing [[racial segregation#USA|segregation]].\n\n==Later career==\nRaby was the Director of the Peace Corps in Ghana from 1979\u201382. Afterwards, he returned to Chicago and was the campaign manager for [[Harold Washington]]'s successful mayoral campaign in 1983. Washington appointed him to head the City of Chicago's Commission on Human Relations in May of 1983.\n\n==Death and recognition==\nRaby collapsed and died from a heart attack on November 23, 1988.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kinginstitute.stanford.edu/encyclopedia/raby-albert|title=Raby, Albert|last=University|first=\u00a9 Stanford|last2=Stanford|date=2017-07-05|website=The Martin Luther King, Jr., Research and Education Institute|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10|last3=California 94305}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004 a Chicago Public High School named after Al Raby was opened. Located in the Garfield Park neighborhood, Al Raby High School for Community and Environment focuses on social justice issues as well as geographical information systems.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{Civil rights movement}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Raby, Albery}}\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:1988 deaths]]\n[[Category:Activists for African-American civil rights]]\n[[Category:People from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Activists from Illinois]]\n", "name_user": "Hunterv23", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(Deleted informmation that had no citatiions or credibility, added citations, fixed grammar and improved writing)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Albert_Raby"}
